 generation of American poets challenges conventional literary histories that place Auden outside the American poetic tradition. In making his case, Wasley pays special attention to three of Auden's most distinguished American inheritors, presenting major new readings of James Merrill, John Ashbery, and Adrienne Rich. The result is a persuasive and compelling demonstration of a novel claim: In order to understand modern American poetry, we need to understand Auden's central place within it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAmerican poetryxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aInfluence (Literary, artistic, etc.)xHistoryx20th century. 0aInfluence (Literary, artistic, etc.)xHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAdrienne Rich.  aAmerica.  aAmerican poetic tradition.  aAmerican poetry.  aAmerican poets.  aDerek Walcott.  aIrving Feldman.  aJames Merrill.  aJames Schuyler.  aJohn Ashbery.  aJohn Hollander.  aLouis Simpson.  aRichard Howard.  aThe Changing Light at Sandover.  aW. H. Auden.  aemigrant.  aemigration.  amodernism.  apost-war poetry.  awomen poets.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400836352zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400836352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400836352.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK